  <article>
    <h1>Ontology & Knowledge Base: Home Services Branding Concepts</h1>
    
    <section>
      <h2>Core Branding Terminology</h2>

      <h3>Brand</h3>
      <p>The sum total of perceptions, associations, and emotions a customer holds about a company. A brand is not a logo—it is the complete experience and reputation of the business in the customer's mind. For home services, brand = trust.</p>

      <h3>Brand Identity</h3>
      <p>The visible, tangible elements a company uses to express its brand: logo, colors, typography, uniforms, vehicle wraps, signage. Identity is what the company creates; image is what customers perceive. The goal is for identity and image to align.</p>

      <h3>Brand Positioning</h3>
      <p>The deliberate decision about how a company wants to be perceived relative to competitors. Effective positioning answers: "We are the only [category] that [differentiator] for [target customer]." Example: "We are the only HVAC company in Phoenix that guarantees same-day service or your diagnostic fee is refunded."</p>

      <h3>Brand Promise</h3>
      <p>The core commitment a business makes to its customers. The most effective home services brand promises are specific, verifiable, and differentiated: "On time or we pay you $50" beats "We value your time."</p>

      <h3>Brand Equity</h3>
      <p>The commercial value derived from customer perception of a brand name. High brand equity allows premium pricing, reduces customer acquisition costs, and accelerates growth. Measurable indicators include unaided awareness, preference rates, and net promoter score.</p>

      <h3>Brand Voice</h3>
      <p>The consistent personality and tone used across all communications. Home services brands typically choose between friendly-expert (approachable, reassuring), authoritative-professional (formal, competent), or local-community (neighborly, familiar). Consistency across channels matters more than which voice is chosen.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Digital Marketing Terminology</h2>

      <h3>Local SEO</h3>
      <p>Search engine optimization targeted at local search results. For home services, this means appearing in the "local pack" (Google Maps results) and organic results for service + location searches like "electrician in Denver." Key factors: Google Business Profile optimization, reviews, citations, and local content.</p>

      <h3>Google Business Profile (GBP)</h3>
      <p>Google's free business listing that appears in Maps and local search results. The most important digital asset for most home services businesses. Optimization includes complete category selection, service areas, photos, regular posts, and systematic review collection.</p>

      <h3>Google Local Services Ads (LSAs)</h3>
      <p>Pay-per-lead Google ads that appear above all other search results, featuring a Google Guarantee or Google Screened badge. Requires background checks and license verification. LSAs are the highest-converting paid advertising channel for many home services categories.</p>

      <h3>NAP Consistency</h3>
      <p>Name, Address, Phone—the core business information that must be identical across all online directories, websites, and listings. Inconsistent NAP data confuses Google and reduces local search ranking.</p>

      <h3>Review Velocity</h3>
      <p>The rate at which a business receives new reviews. Google favors businesses that consistently receive fresh reviews over those with many old reviews. A systematic post-job review request process is essential for maintaining positive review velocity.</p>

      <h3>Customer Acquisition Cost (CAC)</h3>
      <p>Total marketing spend divided by the number of new customers acquired. In home services, CAC varies dramatically by channel: referrals typically cost $5–$20 per customer; paid search averages $80–$300 per lead. Tracking CAC by channel enables rational marketing spend decisions.</p>

      <h3>Lifetime Customer Value (LCV)</h3>
      <p>The total revenue a customer generates across all transactions over the duration of the relationship. Home services customers with high LCV (HVAC maintenance plans, recurring landscaping, house cleaning) justify higher CAC and more investment in retention marketing.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Reputation & Trust Concepts</h2>

      <h3>Net Promoter Score (NPS)</h3>
      <p>A customer loyalty metric measured by asking "How likely are you to recommend us to a friend?" on a 0–10 scale. Promoters (9–10) drive referrals; Detractors (0–6) harm reputation. Home services businesses with NPS above 50 typically have strong organic referral growth.</p>

      <h3>Review Management</h3>
      <p>The systematic process of requesting, monitoring, and responding to customer reviews across Google, Yelp, Angi, and other platforms. Includes automated post-job review requests, timely responses to all reviews (positive and negative), and using feedback to improve service quality.</p>

      <h3>Social Proof</h3>
      <p>The psychological phenomenon where people look to the actions and opinions of others to guide their own decisions. In home services, social proof includes reviews, testimonials, case studies, before-and-after photos, and trust badges (BBB accreditation, Google Guarantee, licensed & insured).</p>

      <h3>Trust Signals</h3>
      <p>Visual or informational cues that communicate reliability and safety. For home services: background check badges, professional licensing numbers, insurance certificates, years in business, professional uniforms, branded vehicles, and Google Guarantee verification.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Marketing Channel Terminology</h2>

      <h3>Pay-Per-Click (PPC)</h3>
      <p>Paid advertising where the advertiser pays each time an ad is clicked. Google Ads PPC is commonly used in home services for high-intent searches. Cost per click varies from $5–50+ depending on market competitiveness and service category.</p>

      <h3>Direct Mail</h3>
      <p>Physical mail sent to households in a target service area. Despite being "old school," direct mail remains one of the highest-ROI channels for home services in many markets, particularly for HVAC tune-up offers, pest control, and landscaping.</p>

      <h3>Vehicle Wrap</h3>
      <p>Full or partial vinyl graphic applied to a service vehicle displaying the company brand, phone number, and services. A single wrapped van generates an estimated 30,000–70,000 impressions per day in urban markets. The highest-ROI physical branding investment for most home services companies.</p>

      <h3>Yard Sign</h3>
      <p>A small sign placed at a job site with the company's branding and phone number. Highly effective in residential neighborhoods where neighbors see the sign while work is being done and call based on curiosity. Particularly effective for landscaping, fencing, roofing, and exterior painting.</p>
    </section>

